2026-05-05 | Lexicographically Smallest String After Corrected K Deletions

	Question
Return the lexicographically smallest string after corrected deletions.
	Key Insight
This is exactly the same idea as:
		Remove K Digits
except now we work with characters.
To obtain the smallest lexicographical string:
		remove larger characters
		when a smaller upcoming character exists.
A monotonic increasing stack gives the optimal result.
	Approach
1.	Compute corrected k.
2.	Check validity:
		if k >= n
				return "-1"
3.	Maintain stack/string.
4.	For every character c:
		while stack not empty
		and stack.back() > c
		and k > 0
				pop
		push c
5.	If deletions still remain:
		remove from end.
6.	If result becomes empty:
		return "-1"
7.	Return result.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool isPowerOfTwo(int n) {
        return n > 0 && (n & (n - 1)) == 0;
    }
    string lexicographicallySmallest(string s, int k) {
        int n = s.size();
        if(isPowerOfTwo(n))
            k /= 2;
        else
            k *= 2;
        if(k >= n)
            return "-1";
        string st;
        for(char c : s) {
            while(!st.empty() &&
                  k > 0 &&
                  st.back() > c) {
                st.pop_back();
                k--;
            }
            st.push_back(c);
        }
        while(k > 0 && !st.empty()) {
            st.pop_back();
            k--;
        }
        if(st.empty())
            return "-1";
        return st;
    }
};
	Key Insight
For the lexicographically smallest string, whenever a smaller character appears, it is beneficial to remove larger characters before it. A monotonic increasing stack efficiently performs these optimal deletions in O(n) time.
